('economics:2-3-supply:exam:ce5216b6', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "A supply curve shows...", "options": ["the equilibrium level of output", "the equilibrium price", "the quantity of a product for sale at each price", "the quantity of a product purchased at each price"], "hint": "Supply is the sellers'' side — what is offered FOR SALE. ''Purchased'' is the demand side, and equilibrium needs both curves.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1 1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — the quantity of a product for sale at each price</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The supply curve maps each price to the quantity producers offer for sale.</li>\n<li>D describes the demand curve; A and B need supply AND demand together.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:7f9fe21f', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "The time period is very important when considering supply. What is the best reason for this?", "options": ["Goods and services vary in how long it takes to change their supply", "Greater efficiency can be gained if more resources are available", "Production costs will rise in the short run but fall in the long run", "The quantity supplied varies directly with the change in price"], "hint": "Think about gold (years to mine) versus pizzas (minutes to make). Why does the TIME window matter when we measure supply?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Goods and services vary in how long it takes to change their supply</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Some products can be supplied quickly, others (gold, houses, trained musicians) take far longer — so supply must always be measured over a stated time period, and PES rises as the time period lengthens.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Nearly half of the candidates gave the correct answer A, with the other responses showing a lack of solid understanding of the importance of time in supply.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:7f3900ca', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "What is the price elasticity of supply of seats at this venue?", "options": ["Greater than 1", "Perfectly elastic", "Perfectly inelastic", "Unitary elastic"], "caseStudy": "<p>A sports venue has a seating capacity of 90 000 people.</p>", "hint": "Can the venue add seats if ticket prices double tonight? The quantity is FIXED whatever the price — which PES is that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Perfectly inelastic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Seating capacity is fixed at 90,000 whatever the price — quantity supplied cannot respond at all, so PES = 0: a vertical supply curve.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:5f344fc5', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "Price elasticity of supply measures the...", "options": ["percentage change in price relative to the percentage change in quantity supplied", "percentage change in quantity supplied relative to a change in income", "ratio of the quantity supplied to the price of the factor inputs", "responsiveness of quantity supplied to a change in the price of the product"], "hint": "It''s QUANTITY SUPPLIED responding to PRICE — not the other way round (that''s option A reversed), and not income or input prices.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — responsiveness of quantity supplied to a change in the price of the product</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>PES = %ΔQs ÷ %ΔP. Option A reverses the ratio; B mixes in income; C is not an elasticity at all.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The correct response to this question was Option D; however, many candidates gave Option A as the correct response.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:68e5a573', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "The diagram shows three supply curves. Which of them has a unitary elasticity?", "options": ["S1", "S2", "S2 and S3", "S1, S2 and S3"], "caseStudy": "<p>The exam paper''s diagram showed three upward-sloping straight-line supply curves on one set of Price/Quantity axes: <strong>S1</strong> cutting the vertical (price) axis, <strong>S2</strong> passing through the origin, and <strong>S3</strong> cutting the horizontal (quantity) axis.</p>", "hint": "The origin rule: ANY straight-line supply curve passing through the ORIGIN has PES = 1, whatever its slope. Which one goes through the origin?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — S2</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Only the straight line through the ORIGIN has unitary PES — along it, the % change in quantity supplied always equals the % change in price.</li>\n<li>A line cutting the price axis (S1) is price elastic; a line cutting the quantity axis (S3) is price inelastic.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:459c8f64', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "If supply is price inelastic, the value of price elasticity of supply will be...", "options": ["greater than one", "greater than the price elasticity of demand", "infinity", "less than one"], "hint": "Inelastic always means the quantity response is proportionally SMALLER than the price change — so the elasticity number is below...?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — less than one</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Price inelastic supply: 0 &lt; PES &lt; 1. Greater than one is elastic; infinity is perfectly elastic; PED is a separate measure entirely.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:545d9ddd', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q13", "question": "Which of the following will cause the supply curve of carrots to shift to the left?", "options": ["A decrease in income tax", "A decrease in the costs of the machinery used to farm carrots", "An increase in the demand for carrots", "An increase in the wages of carrot farmers"], "hint": "A LEFT shift needs supplying to get harder or dearer. Cheaper machinery is the opposite, demand doesn''t shift supply — what raises the farmers'' costs?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — An increase in the wages of carrot farmers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher wages are a rise in production costs — less profitable to supply at every price, so the supply curve shifts left.</li>\n<li>B would shift supply RIGHT; C shifts the demand curve; A affects consumers'' incomes, not carrot production costs.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:2b3673e4', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q15", "question": "Supply means the amount producers are willing and able to provide to the market at a given...", "options": ["level of consumer income", "price", "quantity demanded", "request by the government"], "hint": "Finish the textbook definition: willing and able to provide at a given ______ in a given time period.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — price</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Supply, like demand, is always measured at a given PRICE in a given period of time.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A very high percentage of candidates gave Option B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:39edc728', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16", "question": "An upward sloping supply curve is a straight line starting at the origin. This supply curve is...", "options": ["price elastic", "price elastic to begin with but becomes price inelastic at higher levels of output", "price inelastic", "unitary price elastic"], "hint": "The origin rule again: ANY straight line through the origin has PES = 1 along its whole length — slope is irrelevant.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — unitary price elastic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Along any straight-line supply curve through the origin, the % change in quantity supplied always equals the % change in price — PES = 1 everywhere on it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Option B provided a distractor and common incorrect response to the correct Option, D, in this question. This is possibly due to a lack of familiarity with the price elasticity of a straight-line supply curve that starts at the origin.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:a0fd8e69', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q17", "question": "Which one of the following will lead to a shift in the supply curve to the left?", "options": ["A fall in demand for the good", "A fall in the price of the good", "A subsidy paid to producers", "A tax placed on the production of the good"], "hint": "Left shift = supplying gets dearer or harder. Demand changes and own-price changes never shift supply, and a subsidy shifts it the other way.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — A tax placed on the production of the good</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A production tax raises firms'' effective costs, so less is supplied at every price — a leftward shift.</li>\n<li>A subsidy (C) shifts supply RIGHT; A shifts the demand curve; B causes a movement along the supply curve.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option D as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:b6f2a061', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "The market supply curve for goods and services normally slopes upwards. Which of the following best explains the reason for this?", "options": ["Average costs of production fall as output increases", "Higher prices attract new firms to the market", "Opportunity costs of not producing rise as output increases", "Production costs fall as output increases so profits rise"], "hint": "Why would MORE be supplied at HIGHER prices? Think about what a higher price does to firms currently outside the market.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Higher prices attract new firms to the market</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>At higher prices, production is profitable for more firms, so new entrants add to market supply — one of the key reasons behind the law of supply.</li>\n<li>A and D describe falling costs, which would shift the curve, not explain its slope.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:exam:564a3782', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q22", "question": "Which of the diagrams shows a supply curve with a unitary elasticity of supply?", "options": ["W", "X", "Y", "Z"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/2-3-supply-elasticity-wxyz-extracted.png\" alt=\"Four supply diagrams from the OCR exam paper, each with P and Q axes: W is a steep line cutting the quantity axis, X is a shallow line cutting the price axis, Y is a horizontal line, Z is a straight line through the origin\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:560px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "The origin rule one more time: the unitary supply curve is the straight line through the ORIGIN — whatever its slope.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Z</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Z is the straight line through the origin — unitary PES along its whole length.</li>\n<li>W (cuts the quantity axis) is inelastic; X (cuts the price axis) is elastic; Y (horizontal) is perfectly elastic.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option D as the correct response to this question. Note, those candidates who wrote ''Z'' as their answer were credited with 1 mark.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:237cc0b8', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is the correct definition of supply?", "options": ["The amount producers are willing and able to sell at a given price in a given time period", "The total output an economy could produce", "The amount consumers are willing and able to buy at a given price", "The amount of stock a firm holds in its warehouse"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Supply mirrors the demand definition but for SELLERS: willing AND able to sell, at a given price, in a given time period."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:cb1ee0b8', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following causes a movement ALONG the supply curve for bread (not a shift)?", "options": ["A rise in bakers'' wages", "A change in the price of bread itself", "A new tax on baked goods", "A poor wheat harvest"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Only the good''s OWN price causes a movement along the curve. Wages, harvests and taxes are non-price factors — they shift the whole curve."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:36978d95', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Bad weather ruins the wheat harvest. What happens in the market for bread?", "options": ["The supply curve shifts left", "The supply curve shifts right", "The demand curve shifts left", "A movement up the supply curve"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Wheat is an input for bread — the failed harvest raises costs and cuts what bakers can supply at every price: a leftward supply shift."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:277d1005', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A new machine lets a factory produce twice as much at the same cost. The supply curve...", "options": ["Becomes perfectly inelastic", "Shifts left", "Shifts right", "Stays the same but demand shifts"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Improved technology lowers average costs, so the firm is willing to supply more at every price — a rightward shift."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:7805172e', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The price of a good rises by 10% and quantity supplied rises by 5%. PES is...", "options": ["0.5, so supply is price inelastic", "2, so supply is price elastic", "15, so supply is unitary", "0.5, so supply is price elastic"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "PES = %ΔQs ÷ %ΔP = 5 ÷ 10 = 0.5. Less than 1 means supply responds less than price — price inelastic."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:9285446d', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which product is most likely to have price ELASTIC supply?", "options": ["Gold, which must be discovered, extracted and refined", "Seats at a 90,000-capacity stadium", "Fresh strawberries in mid-winter", "Tinned food made in a factory with spare capacity"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Easily stored products made with spare capacity can be ramped up quickly when price rises. Gold''s long production time and fixed stadium seats make those inelastic."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:7e5a1dd8', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The supply of seats for tonight''s sold-out concert is best described as...", "options": ["Unitary", "Perfectly price elastic", "Price elastic", "Perfectly price inelastic"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The venue''s seats are fixed whatever the ticket price — PES = 0, a vertical supply curve."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:13165f0a', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The government pays farmers a subsidy for every tonne of vegetables grown. The supply curve for vegetables...", "options": ["Shifts right", "Shifts left", "Does not move — there is a movement along it", "Becomes vertical"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A subsidy effectively lowers the farmer''s costs, so more is supplied at every price — a rightward shift."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:c17a3124', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following would IMPROVE a firm''s price elasticity of supply?", "options": ["Training each worker for exactly one task", "Selling only perishable goods", "Holding spare production capacity", "Cutting all warehouse space"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Spare capacity lets the firm ramp output up quickly when price rises. Perishables, no storage and rigid job roles all make supply LESS responsive."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:mcq:9794f004', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Aldi and Lidl enter the UK supermarket industry. The market supply curve for groceries...", "options": ["Shifts left", "Shifts right", "Stays the same", "Becomes perfectly elastic"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "More producers in the market means more supplied at every price — market supply (the sum of all individual supplies) shifts right."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:775ea422', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The supply curve slopes upwards from left to right."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Higher prices make supplying more profitable and attract new firms, so quantity supplied rises with price — the law of supply."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:423c3f7f', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A fall in the price of a good shifts its supply curve to the left."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The good''s own price never shifts its supply curve — a price fall causes a movement DOWN the curve (a contraction of supply)."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:b3ef6a02', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A government subsidy shifts the supply curve to the right."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "A subsidy lowers the firm''s effective costs, so it is willing to supply more at every price."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:7858725d', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "If PES is less than 1, supply is price inelastic."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "PES < 1 means the % change in quantity supplied is smaller than the % change in price — the definition of inelastic supply."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:c927853f', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The supply of seats at a stadium with fixed capacity is perfectly price elastic."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "It''s perfectly price INELASTIC — the quantity cannot change whatever the price, a vertical supply curve. Perfectly elastic is the horizontal one."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:adb1b6ef', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Any straight-line supply curve passing through the origin has unitary elasticity, whatever its slope."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Through the origin, the % change in quantity always equals the % change in price — PES = 1. A favourite exam trap: slope doesn''t matter here."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:6c74c6d6', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "New firms entering a market shift the market supply curve to the right."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Market supply is all individual supplies added together — more producers means more supplied at every price, like Aldi and Lidl entering UK groceries."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:tf:0a2febed', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "If a firm''s total revenue rises, its profit must rise too."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Profit = total revenue − total costs. If costs rise faster than revenue, profit FALLS. OCR flagged this exact misconception in a real mark scheme."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:learn:ce5216b6', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is supply?", "reading": "<p><strong>Supply</strong> is the amount of a product that producers are <strong>willing and able</strong> to sell, <strong>at a given price, in a given period of time</strong>.</p>\n<h4>All four parts of the definition earn marks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Willing</strong> — the producer wants to sell the product.</li>\n<li><strong>Able</strong> — the producer has the means to supply it. A farmer with 5 cows might <em>like</em> to supply 1,000 litres of milk a day, but isn''t able to — so that is not part of their supply.</li>\n<li><strong>At a given price</strong> — e.g. £9.99.</li>\n<li><strong>In a given time period</strong> — e.g. per day or per week.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Individual and market supply</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Individual supply</strong> — the amount ONE firm is willing to supply at each price.</li>\n<li><strong>Market supply</strong> — all the individual supply curves <strong>added together</strong>: the total supplied by every firm in the market at each price.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The law of supply — and WHY it holds</h4>\n<p>Quantity supplied varies <strong>directly</strong> with price: as price rises, quantity supplied rises. Three reasons:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>At higher prices <strong>existing firms earn more per unit</strong>, so they are willing to supply more.</li>\n<li>Producing more can push a firm''s <strong>costs up</strong> (bigger premises, overtime), so it needs a higher price to justify it.</li>\n<li>Rising prices <strong>attract new firms</strong> into the market that previously found it not worthwhile.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Drawing rules</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The supply curve slopes <strong>upwards from bottom-left to top-right</strong>.</li>\n<li>Label the axes <strong>Price</strong> and <strong>Quantity</strong>, and label the curve <strong>S</strong> (or Supply) — an unlabelled diagram scores no marks.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A supply curve shows...", "options": ["The quantity of a product for sale at each price", "The equilibrium price", "The quantity of a product purchased at each price", "The equilibrium level of output"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Supply is what producers offer FOR SALE at each price — what is purchased at each price is demand. This exact MCQ opens the real 2.3 exam paper."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-3-supply:learn:158dfb71', 'economics', 'economics:2-3-supply', '2.3 Supply', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Movements along vs shifts of the supply curve", "reading": "<p>Exactly the same logic as demand — but learn the supply list separately, because mixing the two lists up is one of the commonest exam errors.</p>\n<h4>Movement ALONG the curve — caused ONLY by the good''s own price</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Price rises → quantity supplied rises → movement UP the curve = an <strong>expansion</strong> of supply.</li>\n<li>Price falls → quantity supplied falls → movement DOWN the curve = a <strong>contraction</strong> of supply.</li>\n<li><strong>Key exam insight:</strong> a movement along the supply curve can only happen because the <strong>DEMAND curve shifted</strong> and changed the price. Real 6-markers test exactly this.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>SHIFT of the whole curve — the 8 factors to learn</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Costs of production</strong> — costs rise (wages, raw materials, crude oil for petrol producers) → LEFT; costs fall → RIGHT.</li>\n<li><strong>Taxes</strong> — higher taxes like VAT raise firms'' effective costs → LEFT.</li>\n<li><strong>Subsidies</strong> — a government subsidy lowers a firm''s costs → RIGHT (e.g. subsidising firms to extend broadband to regional areas).</li>\n<li><strong>Technology</strong> — new or improved technology lowers average costs → RIGHT.</li>\n<li><strong>Climate / weather</strong> — failed crops → LEFT; bumper crops → RIGHT. Bad weather also delays construction → LEFT.</li>\n<li><strong>Number of producers</strong> — new firms entering (Aldi and Lidl joining the UK supermarket industry) → RIGHT; firms leaving → LEFT.</li>\n<li><strong>Size of existing firms</strong> — existing firms growing significantly → RIGHT.</li>\n<li><strong>Government regulations</strong> — new rules add compliance costs → LEFT; deregulation → RIGHT.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Consequences for consumers and producers</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Supply shifts right → price falls, quantity rises → cheaper for consumers; each unit earns producers less.</li>\n<li>Supply shifts left → price rises, quantity falls → consumers pay more; some may go without.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "The wages of carrot farmers rise. What happens in the market for carrots?", "options": ["The demand curve shifts left", "The supply curve shifts right", "The supply curve shifts left", "A movement along the supply curve"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Higher wages are a rise in production costs — supplying carrots is less profitable at every price, so the whole supply curve shifts left. This is a real exam MCQ."}'::jsonb)
